hire, England","Chebsey, Staffordshire, England":"Chebsey, Staffordshire, England"},"nl":{"2 February 1359–Bef 1 March 1410":"2 februari 1359–vóór 1 maart 1410","1359–1410":"1359–1410","1360–Female":"1360–Overleden","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1384–1419":"1384–1419","1340–1367":"1340–1367","1341–1369":"1341–1369","October 1367":"oktober 1367","20 July 1369":"20 juli 1369","Bef 1 March 1410":"vóór 1 maart 1410","2 February 1359":"2 februari 1359","1341":"1341","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1359":"1359","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1419":"1419","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Leamington Spa, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Chebsey, Staffordshire, England":"Chebsey, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"2 February 1359–Bef 1 March 1410":"2 February 1359–before 1 March 1410","1359–1410":"1359–1410","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1384–1419":"1384–1419","1340–1367":"1340–1367","1341–1369":"1341–1369","October 1367":"October 1367","20 July 1369":"20 July 1369","Bef 1 March 1410":"before 1 March 1410","2 February 1359":"2 February 1359","1341":"1341","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1359":"1359","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1419":"1419","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Leamington Spa, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Chebsey, Staffordshire, England":"Chebsey, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hastings","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from Hastings (Sussex), near which the English army was defeated by the Normans in 1066. The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Hǣsta</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>. In the latter part of the 12th century, at the time of William the Lion, the surname was taken to Scotland, where it assimilated instances of the native Scottish surname <b>Harestane</b>.","English: variant of   Hasting   with Middle English genitival <i>-s</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hOistín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Oistín</i>’, the Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Augustine</i> (see   Austin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hasting","meanings":["English: from the Norman personal name <i>Hastang</i>, <i>Hastenc</i>, <i>Hasten</i> (Old Norse <i>Hásteinn</i> ‘high’ + ‘stone’). See also   Hastings  ."]},{"name":"Heston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Heston (Middlesex) or Histon (Cambridgeshire). The Middlesex placename derives from Old English <i>hǣs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, while the Cambridgeshire placename may derive from Old English <i>hyse</i> ‘shoot, tendril’, also ‘son, youth’, + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish (Mayo): variant of   Hastings  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Hastings was born on 2 February 1359, in Chebsey, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John de Hastang, was 20 and her mother, Mauld Trussell, was 19. She married Ralph Stafford in 1373. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died before 1 March 1410."},"et":{"2 February 1359–Bef 1 March 1410":"2. veebruar 1359–enne 1. märtsi 1410","1359–1410":"1359–1410","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1384–1419":"1384–1419","1340–1367":"1340–1367","1341–1369":"1341–1369","October 1367":"oktoober 1367","20 July 1369":"20. juuli 1369","Bef 1 March 1410":"enne 1. märtsi 1410","2 February 1359":"2. veebruar 1359","1341":"1341","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1359":"1359","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1419":"1419","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leamington Spa, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Chebsey, Staffordshire, England":"Chebsey, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"2 February 1359–Bef 1 March 1410":"2. helmikuuta 1359–ennen vuotta 1. maaliskuuta 1410","1359–1410":"1359–1410","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1384–1419":"1384–1419","1340–1367":"1340–1367","1341–1369":"1341–1369","October 1367":"lokakuu 1367","20 July 1369":"20. heinäkuuta 1369","Bef 1 March 1410":"ennen vuotta 1. maaliskuuta 1410","2 February 1359":"2. helmikuuta 1359","1341":"1341","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1359":"1359","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1419":"1419","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Leamington Spa, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Chebsey, Staffordshire, England":"Chebsey, Staffordshire, England"},"fr":{"2 February 1359–Bef 1 March 1410":"2 février 1359–avant 1 mars 1410","1359–1410":"1359–1410","1360–Female":"1360–Décédée","1355–141